so, calling `repaint` on the instance of `Display` in the `GameLoop` will have no effect, as it&#39;s not actually displayed on the screen.

Instead, you should be passing the same instance of `Display` to both `GUI` and `GameLoop` ... although I&#39;d be making use of `interface`s to do this, as `GameLoop` should be doing NOTHING else to the component.

This is a concept known as [Dependency Injection](https://medium.com/groupon-eng/dependency-injection-in-java-9e9438aa55ae)

This...

    @Override
    public void run() {
        display.getVariableValues();
        display.repaint();
    }

is some what pointless.  As it&#39;s only going to execute once and then exit (and the associated thread will be terminated).

Instead, you should be setting up some kind of loop which will continue to run (until you request it to stop via some kind of flag).  This is pretty basic socket handling.

You should also consider either making a `protected` inner class that implements `Runnable` or make use of anonymous class instead, for example...

    t = new Thread(new Runnable() {
        @Override
        public void run() {
            // Do you game loop logic here
            // or call a protected method to do it
        }
    });

Implementing the `run` interface will expose the `public` `run` method, and realistically, no one else should be calling `run`

